  <main>

    <!-- QUICK ANSWER -->
    <div class="quick-answer">
      <h2>The Short Answer</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Yes — <strong>eating 30–40g of protein before bed is one of the highest-leverage habits</strong> for men over 40</li>
        <li>Sleep is your longest fast — 7–8 hours with no amino acids available. Muscle protein synthesis slows without them</li>
        <li><strong>Cottage cheese and casein are ideal</strong> — they digest slowly over 5–7 hours, matching the overnight window perfectly</li>
        <li>The old "don't eat after 7pm" rule was about weight management — <strong>a different goal, a different game</strong></li>
        <li>This is not a large meal. It's a targeted 30–40g snack that covers your overnight window without disrupting sleep</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- INTRO -->
    <p>I'm 64. I grew up hearing the same rule most men my age did: don't eat after 7pm. It was everywhere in the 80s and 90s — fitness books, diet columns, even credible voices in the health space were repeating it. The idea was simple: your metabolism slows at night, eating late leads to fat storage, so stop eating after dinner and let your body rest.</p>

    <p>It wasn't bad advice for what it was trying to do. Late-night eating is a real driver of excess calorie consumption for a lot of people — the mindless chips and ice cream after 9pm adds up. Cutting that off makes sense as a weight management strategy.</p>

    <p>But here's the problem: that rule was designed to help people lose weight. <strong>It was never designed for men over 40 who are trying to hold onto muscle.</strong> Those are two different goals, and they don't always share the same playbook.</p>

