      </div>
      <div class="stat-box">
        <div class="stat-num">30–40g</div>
        <div class="stat-label">pre-sleep protein dose shown to support overnight muscle protein synthesis in men over 40</div>
      </div>
      <div class="stat-box">
        <div class="stat-num">5–7 hrs</div>
        <div class="stat-label">how long casein and cottage cheese release amino acids — matching the overnight window</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Where the "Don't Eat After 7pm" Rule Came From</h2>

    <p>The advice had real roots. Researchers and fitness experts in the 80s and 90s were observing that people who ate late at night tended to consume more calories overall, sleep worse, and struggle more with weight management. The "stop eating at 7pm" rule was a behavioral guardrail — a simple heuristic to prevent the extra 400 calories that tend to sneak in after dinner.</p>

    <p>It worked for that goal. But the fitness conversation at that time was almost entirely about weight loss and cardiovascular health. The aerobics movement — Dr. Kenneth Cooper's influence was enormous in that era — framed fitness primarily through the lens of heart health and calorie burn. Muscle preservation for men over 40 simply wasn't the focus. Nobody was talking about anabolic resistance or muscle protein synthesis thresholds. The tools to measure those things barely existed.</p>

    <div class="then-now">
      <div class="then-card">
        <div class="card-era">The 80s / 90s Rule</div>
        <div class="card-rule">"Don't eat after 7pm"</div>
        <div class="card-goal">Goal: weight management, reduce late-night calorie overconsumption. Good advice for that specific problem.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="now-card">
        <div class="card-era">The Updated Rule After 40</div>
        <div class="card-rule">"Eat 30–40g of protein before bed"</div>
        <div class="card-goal">Goal: muscle maintenance, close the overnight amino acid gap. Same discipline, different objective.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The rule wasn't wrong. It was just aimed at a different target. Now that you're playing a different game — one where holding onto muscle mass is the priority — the playbook needs an update.</p>

    <h2>What Actually Happens to Muscle While You Sleep</h2>

    <p>Sleep is not a passive state for your muscles. It's actually the primary window for muscle repair and growth — the time when your body processes the training stimulus from the day and rebuilds muscle tissue. Growth hormone peaks during deep sleep. The cellular machinery for protein synthesis is running.</p>

    <p>The problem is the fuel supply.</p>

    <p>When you eat your last meal at 6 or 7pm and go to sleep at 10pm, you're entering a fast that lasts until breakfast — potentially 12 or 13 hours. During that window, your blood amino acid levels drop. And when amino acids aren't available, muscle protein synthesis slows. For men over 40 dealing with <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">anabolic resistance</a>, that slowdown is more significant than it would be for a younger man. The machinery is running, but the raw materials ran out hours ago.</p>

