    <p>A pre-sleep protein dose — specifically a slow-digesting source — closes that gap. Instead of your muscles running on empty from midnight to 7am, amino acids are still trickling in at 2am, 4am, 6am. The repair machinery stays fed through the window it needs most.</p>

    <h2>Why Casein and Cottage Cheese — Not Whey</h2>

    <p>Not all protein sources work equally well before bed, and this is where the type of protein matters. Whey protein digests quickly — amino acids peak in the bloodstream within 60–90 minutes and drop off fast. That makes it ideal post-workout, when you want a rapid spike. But before bed, a fast spike and quick drop-off means you're back to an amino acid gap by midnight.</p>

    <p>Casein is the answer. It forms a gel in the stomach and digests slowly — releasing amino acids steadily over 5 to 7 hours. That sustained release aligns almost perfectly with a full night of sleep. You eat at 9:30pm and your muscles are still receiving amino acids at 3am.</p>

    <p>Cottage cheese is naturally high in casein — it's one of the best whole-food casein sources available, and it's something most men over 40 actually have in their fridge. No powder, no mixing, no planning required.</p>

