    <!-- MYTH BOX -->
    <div class="myth-box">
      <div class="myth-label">The Concern Most Men Have</div>
      <h3>"Won't Eating Before Bed Make Me Gain Weight?"</h3>
      <p>This is the 80s rule talking — and it's worth addressing directly. <strong>Eating protein before bed does not cause weight gain in isolation.</strong> Weight gain is determined by total caloric intake over time, not by when a specific meal happens.</p>
      <p>What the "don't eat after 7pm" rule was actually preventing was mindless late-night snacking — the extra 400–600 calories of chips, ice cream, or leftovers that people tend to consume out of habit rather than hunger. That's a real problem worth solving.</p>
      <p>A targeted 30–40g cottage cheese snack before bed is a completely different thing. It's roughly 160–220 calories, almost entirely protein, with minimal fat and carbohydrates. If your total daily calories are reasonable, this snack doesn't move the needle on body composition — but it <strong>meaningfully supports overnight muscle repair</strong>. Different goal. Different strategy.</p>
    </div>

