    <p>Keep it simple. The cottage cheese option requires zero preparation — open the container, grab a spoon. That's the whole routine. You're more likely to stick with a habit that takes 90 seconds than one that requires planning.</p>

    <p>If you want to see how pre-sleep protein fits into a full day of eating that hits 120g, the <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">120g visual breakdown</a> maps it out meal by meal.</p>

    <h2>The Rule Wasn't Wrong. The Goal Changed.</h2>

    <p>This is worth saying clearly, because it matters: the men who gave us the "don't eat after 7pm" advice weren't wrong. They were solving a real problem with the tools and knowledge they had. Dr. Cooper's aerobics framework genuinely improved cardiovascular health for millions of people. The late-night eating guardrail helped a lot of people manage their weight.</p>

    <p>But the goal has changed. At 40, 50, 60 — muscle maintenance isn't a vanity project. It's directly tied to metabolic health, insulin sensitivity, mobility, injury prevention, and long-term independence. <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/sarcopenia-men-over-40/" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">Sarcopenia</a> — the age-related loss of muscle mass — is one of the most significant health risks men over 40 face, and most men have no idea it's happening to them.</p>

    <p>Protecting the overnight window with a targeted protein snack is one of the simplest, lowest-cost interventions available. It doesn't require a gym. It doesn't require a prescription. It requires a container of cottage cheese and the willingness to update a 40-year-old rule.</p>

